					<p>
	     To coincide with today’s <a href="http://pixelandtonic.com/blog/craft-1.2">Craft 1.2 release</a>, we just took the wraps off of Craft’s <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/" target="_blank">brand new website</a>. The site sports a new design that better compliments Craft itself, and we’ve added <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/pricing" target="_blank">Pricing</a>, <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/help" target="_blank">Help &amp; Support</a>, and <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/resources" target="_blank">Resources</a> pages. We’ve also integrated Craft’s <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/docs" target="_blank">Documentation</a> and <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/showcase" target="_blank">Showcase</a> into the site, which used to live on separate domains.
</p>
<!--pagebreak-->
<p>
	 <img src="/content/blog/2013-09/buildwithcraft_2x.jpg" width="552" alt="The new buildwithcraft.com">
</p>
<p>
	     Craft’s documentation has been completely overhauled, with the goal of making it much easier to find what you’re looking for. To that end, we’ve separated the docs into three parts: <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/docs" target="_blank">Documentation</a>, <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/docs/templating" target="_blank">Templating Reference</a>, and <a href="http://buildwithcraft.com/docs/plugins" target="_blank">Plugin Development</a>. That gave us the opportunity to reorganize their sidebar navigations, bringing all the good stuff right up to the top.
</p>
<p>
	     You’ll probably notice that the new site is running a heck of a lot faster than the old site. That’s thanks to its new home on <a href="http://arcustech.com/" target="_blank">ArcusTech</a>, an amazing new web host coming soon from the creators of <a href="http://www.enginehosting.com/" target="_blank">EngineHosting</a>. The guys ArcusTech were kind enough to let us move buildwithcraft.com over to their new infrastructure, and the speeds are incredibly impressive. Page load times are about <strong>5X</strong> faster than they were on our old server, and get this: they’re even <strong>2X</strong> faster than our own local hosts! We have absolutely no idea how they do it, but we are in awe.
</p>
